{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"32c74c43-f65f-4b02-8f35-e035c7776ff0","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — If enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited` before running), they land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nSince NativeAOT produces a native binary (no CoreCLR, no `createdump`), macOS treats it like any other native process. The Apple crash report (`.ips` file) will contain the faulting thread, stack trace, and register state — usually enough to start debugging.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d798214-a0fc-4d4f-a781-dba1ff4b74de","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":260,"requestId":"CB03:3454B1:21EB0D9:2532808:6A0529BC"},"id":"6a81d8f3-f8ae-45fc-b609-02c95e65f88b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:47:48.315Z","parentId":"05c5470e-cbbe-436a-82e7-0ceab4da5941"}
